- ts: 2026-04-29T00:00:00Z
  event: clarify_critic
  feature: instrument-orchestrator-round-subprocess-with-token-cost-telemetry
  findings:
    - "Intent clarity High asserts a single unambiguous outcome ('bucket exists in the per-skill rollup'), but Open Question 2 in the source explicitly leaves open whether to extend the dispatch schema, mint a synthetic feature value, or emit a separate orchestrator-scope event with a parallel aggregator — these are materially different deliverables, not just *how* questions."
    - "Intent clarity High treats the ticket 111 R11/R12 motivation as concrete, but Open Question 4 explicitly raises that the inline-read prompt may already be retired by the time this is worked, making the originating value case potentially moot — an intent that may be obsolete before implementation is not 'unambiguous and complete.'"
    - "Scope boundedness High cites Affected files as authoritative, but the open questions show the actual file footprint is contingent on design choices: schema-mapping option B (parallel aggregator) requires new aggregator code beyond 'confirm aggregator handles a session-scope record,' and the emission-point question contemplates a dispatch.py wrapper that exceeds a Literal extension."
    - "Requirements alignment High cites pipeline.md 'Metrics and Cost Tracking,' but the requirement specifies 'per-feature metrics, tier aggregates, and calibration summaries' — the ticket explicitly notes orchestrator-round 'has model+tier ... but no feature — it operates at session scope.' That is a partial conflict (data-model extension), not clean alignment."
    - "Criticality High applies the rubric mechanically without engaging with the ticket's own signals to the contrary: priority is `low` in frontmatter, and the ticket scopes itself as observational (no optimization, no model-tier reshuffling, no backfill)."
    - "Intent clarity High treats the work as purely additive telemetry, but Open Question 1 (output-format choice) flags that switching Popen invocation flags could disrupt existing real-time stdout consumers like NOTIFY: parsing — meaning the implementation may regress unrelated runner functionality."
  dispositions:
    apply: 4
    dismiss: 2
    ask: 0
  applied_fixes:
    - "Added research open question covering design choice between extending dispatch.py's per-skill schema (with synthetic <session> feature value) vs adding a parallel session-scope event channel with its own aggregator (Finding 0)."
    - "Acknowledged file-footprint contingency in scope boundedness reasoning: behavioral scope (forward-going telemetry; excludes batch-runner, optimization, backfill) is bounded, but file count varies with the design choice surfaced in Finding 0 (Finding 2)."
    - "Revised Requirements alignment from High to Partial: pipeline.md 'Metrics and Cost Tracking' is per-feature; this ticket extends the data model to session scope. Not a conflict — an extension (Finding 3)."
    - "Added research open question covering output-format choice's compatibility with existing NOTIFY: stdout parsing in the runner; choice between stream-json and end-of-run json must be evaluated against real-time stdout consumers (Finding 5)."
  dismissals:
    - finding_index: 1
      rationale: "The body's opening paragraph establishes a standalone value case independent of R11/R12: orchestrator-round token costs are 'invisible to the per-skill rollup' regardless of any specific consumer. R11/R12 closure is a bonus, not load-bearing motivation. If research discovers R11/R12 is moot the §4 complexity/value gate will catch over-engineering; intent clarity at the goal level is unaffected."
    - finding_index: 4
      rationale: "Priority (when to work on it) and criticality (blast radius if broken) are orthogonal axes per the lifecycle rubric. Overnight-runner subprocess changes default to high criticality regardless of priority. The 'observational' framing is undermined by Finding 5's NOTIFY regression risk — switching Popen flags is not purely additive. Criticality High stands."
  status: ok
